Parliament does not support an amendment that gives Timoshenko freedom.
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in amending the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to repeal an article that condemned the leader of the opposition, Yulia Timoshenko.
The amendment that would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the bill on the commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider Timoshenko's appeal in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is the political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, which condemned the former Prime Minister, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
Ratification would require 226 votes.
