V Need for Speed: The escape is taking place in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk has become a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and negligent mistakes.
Ambiations have been satisfied to some extent, but it doesn't matter, since no one clearly wanted to do too much work.
Before the new version, the sub-heading "Escape" had a great deal of hope.
It was expected to move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; the demonstration versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the genre of the race games.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main hero gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end a lot is different from what we expected.
The game is a rather good arcade race, but the overall impression is a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, in fact, it's not a mistake, it's an expression of the inexplicable ribbon of the developers.
The adventure is starting very well.
You're part of a story that, Jack, is the main hero, is solving some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in the car on the west coast, San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of 10 stages divided into more than 50 races.
This means that each race is on its own route, and some steps are taking place in a different and interesting environment.
So there's no feeling that the game is the same all the time.
While the schedule is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is good to see some tracks.
And yet the game is not very emotional.
Although driving through the desert, it's very nice to be on the fall suburbs or high in the snow mountains.
And, in addition, the races, from time to time, revive an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you get into a sand storm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get under the avalanche.
The individual races are rather well-organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while, you try to outstrip a few rivals (essentially a regular race); then you try to improve time (a standard race with a second); or you compete with one opponent.
Among other things, you come across the police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack is running away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not that hard.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much less than you could expect (only three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for a game, because it's not a thing that's annoying; given all the above, it's one of the things that make a game more busy.
The race model follows from previous models.
It means it's no longer a special thing, but it can't be considered a lack.
If you're looking for a real life simulation, you're gonna have to look elsewhere.
And yet this driving model is very good for dynamic races, although better options can be found on the market.
So far, so good.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don't expect a game like this to be a complex change or a clash, but if you have no idea what's going on with the object, like your car does, something's wrong.
Usually, by driving or passing by cars in a dense stream, you sometimes touch another car a little bit, and yet sometimes in a very similar situation, your car starts to be furious.
Or the two of us broke up.
It's not important because of the relaunch system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
The reruns are so that if you break up or go far off the track, the game brings you back to the point where it was interrupted.
However, only five relaunches are available for each race.
If you use all of them, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work out, but you can't rely on it.
Sometimes it's not enough to relaunch, and you have to learn a separate section of the race.
The important disadvantage of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to go in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars at a certain location in the same configuration, whether you come first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations where you see your rival moving easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you're there, the cars are already located so that you either have to cross them or drop the speed.
It doesn't matter when you're next to them; it's all arranged in such a way that the situation always happens just before your nose.
The rivals have other advantages as well.
During the game, you find a few places where, regardless of time, the same rival is overtaking you in the same place.
This is particularly obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your rival must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's on his way to you, he's making your view worse, leading to one or more accidents on this site.
You can understand an attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to cause irritation.
It's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the game is exciting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
No matter what makes you miss, the concept of five unique tracks, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to track the gas stations on the way, because it's them that your car can change, even though in most cases the ones you already have are enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports machines are suitable for cities; powerful American cars for direct sections of the highway; and exotic super-sports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main mode is closely linked to the challenge mode; it is a race on individual sites that you will recognize as you proceed.
This is where you win for your personal business both the medals and the glasses common to the challenge regimes and the story.
Many opportunities are available for a higher level of driving, from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares the results you have achieved with those of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here is another shortcoming that is difficult to understand; this is an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car are going into a subway tunnel, where you're going through the tracks in the dark.
Your speedometer shows a figure of between 150 and 200 km / h (let's think so) when a subway train is suddenly on the back of you, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our drafting has been discussing whether, at the time of the game's creation, no one really thought for a second, or whether its creators really think we're such a fool.
The technical component of the game is not special; but the overall impression of the video is, for the most part, pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
While it is regrettable that, in some critical points, the quality of the record is sometimes very high.
This is particularly the case with a large number of participants, where a good record would not be of much help to you either.
The sound is fine; the soundtrack is for an amateur.
In order to please the widest possible youth audience, the soundtrack 'has been made up of different styles'; but it is unlikely that many people will buy a game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: The escape is rather disorderly.
If the game were to avoid clearly unnecessary mistakes, we could say in earnest that the escape is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a sense of non-completion.
Of course, it's a good entertainment, but get ready to be blinded as a searchlight of the airport.
