Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five State-owned tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely limited, travel agencies at the time were mostly selling tours to the socialist bloc countries.
Thus, Czech tourists were on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which caused significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel on its own, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was required; another individual journey was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies offered to the West, but they either had to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have "good friends" at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The foreign exchange permit was necessary for travel to the West and was not issued to politically insecure people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit, it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West.
Most often, the Checks have spent their leave at home, which has resulted in a large number of cottages and summer houses, a habit that has continued to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While, until 1989, leave in the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travel, last year the Checkhs held 4.5 million leave in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer understand, is that until 1989 we were unable to visit the most popular Croatia today, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In early 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries of Western Europe was cancelled, which led to a huge wave of short-term travel, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia could not have been full of travel to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at that time was insufficient for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (canned, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and after decades our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have grown, which has led to another important situation around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, and since the past, flights have now become extremely cheap because of the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the cheques did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed world countries except the US, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant development in the history of the post-revolution travel took place in 2000, with a large demand leading to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will be on 12 exotic tracks.
At present, about 100,000 Chekhs visit exotic countries every year!
Another important development of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States cancelled the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists, so that our country has become a permanent member of the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, more than half of their leave was held abroad (50.3 per cent); for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during the period of leave abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
