It's easy. I just need to get on Facebook.
"We realized it was not easy to get to them," said Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of the recently published report on the European Cyber-populism of the British Research Centre DEMOS.
The wealth of personal data on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett that researchers could easily use the site's promotional tool to highlight the necessary population group with scientific precision - that market scientists have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing group fans all over Europe and then gave them an ad, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, it offered a user a survey that asked them about their level of education, about violence and optimism about their own future.
With Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, even without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," says Bartlett.
Some results are less striking: online supporters of right-wing groups are most often young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with their offline activity are more reasonable, more democratic and less aggressive than those who only hide behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is only one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything, from health to social trends, which are expressed in "Leikas," positions on the wall and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three records per day, Facebook's "super-relevant information" is a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles called the site in the heading by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have had to join the party and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all of this, you're talking to them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and study social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunken works on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students, such as their dormitories, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunk status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christ, co-author of Moreno and Director of the Centre for Child Health, Conduct and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook also continuously extracts different types of data on its users.
The site & apos; s data processing team processed statistics on the status of relations and Valentine & apos; s Day, voter turnout in mid-2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that is available only to them, the cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not, in exchange for an opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away from you, the site can process your personal data.
But how can it be when Facebook users become participants in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined rules for offline research, online data are available to the public.
"I don't think many users even thought that a researcher could watch their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public pages of students in Facebook.
"As far as they could imagine, it was only between them and their friends."
The question of methodology then arises.
Even the offline has no guarantee that the object of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to know how much information is in the profile and on the user's page.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things," said Selvin.
That is why, despite its years of work in technology research, Selvin thinks that the notebook and the pen are still the best research tools to use.
"Nothing can replace a way into the real world and a relationship with real people," he said.
"It is assumed that social research is about social research, and most social research still takes place offline."
