Climate problems have slowed the economy down.
During the first year of the rule of Mario Lopez, unemployment and the illegal labour market increased in Sinaloa, foreign financing fell and the economy was weakened.
2011 - a year that will enter the economic history of Sinaloa as the first year-related Government of Mario López Valdes, also known as the year of change, which has given rise to great hopes for economic development, but given the adverse climatic conditions of the beginning of the year, there has been no growth, but there has been a decline in key economic development indicators.
The low temperatures of February have not only led to the loss of millions for the agricultural sector, but have limited the growth of the public economy, resulting in a reduction of 3.6 per cent in total economic activity in the first half of the year, mainly due to a historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on areas affected by the frost provided by the Council for Sustainable Rural Development of Mexico, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 per cent were affected in whole and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially affected, with vegetables, maize and waste being the main crops affected.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters, an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate was recorded, from January to March 55,053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, the share increased to 5.28 per cent in the second quarter, and from July to September it continued to 6.19 per cent, an increase of over 74,000 Sinaloa, an increase of 18,969 over the first half.
Liquidity reduction
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year has been discussed by many factors, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the increase in unemployment can be attributed indirectly to actions taken in public policy.
"What we see now is an increase in unemployment, which is associated with several factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market to limit the resources imposed by the law that was adopted in Congress to combat money-laundering, because it is difficult for people who are illegally in possession of dollars to work with, invest and use them in something," he said.
Immigration stopped
Lopez Cervantes said that there was also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state for work abroad was limited in the United States, primarily because of entry difficulties, and, second, because once they entered, they already face very many difficulties in finding work, so that a group of people remain and demand jobs here in the state, as a result of the increase in unemployment," he said.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market is becoming worse when attention is drawn to the large number of labour-dominated violations, according to INEGI, that 60,.38 per cent of the active population of the State is working without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and job irregularities, a further reminder of work in the State is provided by low wages; in the State, the lowest wages in the country, according to records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,552 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
FDI reduction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high unemployment rate in 2011, the Ministry of Finance reported the largest foreign direct investment outflows in the last 10 years that from January to July, state FDI amounted to $630,697, a decrease of 87.74 per cent, compared with $5,543,312 in the same period last year.
For its part, the Department of Economic Development of the State Government recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which was mainly made available to service companies.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn, the State Government requested, during the State Congress in July, the approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos that would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos had been approved at the local level, and until November no sector of the State economy had expected debt benefits.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdes shows a lack of government capacity.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, President of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the State Government itself, during 2011.
"The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year has been really low, we have to work hard to recover the positions lost this year, we have to redouble our efforts in 2012, we have not been able to agree on the efforts of all and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowdown
Lopez Loredo said that events such as early frost have stopped the state economy this year and its efficiency and growth have been limited.
"The low levels of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not becoming fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year, we close it below our expectations," he said.
Revision of direction
Theodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Confederation of Employers of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, said that the state needed to continue its most dynamic production activity.
"In general, we have found that we have been working on this, we believe that a long-term programme must be developed that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has," he said.
Work to be undertaken
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction in order to better guide the Government & apos; s efforts.
"In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, there is little progress in terms of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration had shown progress in its own manner of public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is beginning to get involved, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is aware that much more needs to be done," he said.
