The Court will approve the "transition to digital television" in Mexico in 2015.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (Supreme Court) rejected the constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which postponed the so-called "digital television transition" from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required for its cancellation.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his mandate by issuing a decree detailing the actions for the transition to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because of the lack of a qualified majority of the eight votes required for the court to speak on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme is a right under the law of the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Saldzar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to challenge the decree and to support the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned therein with regard to the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules for action to be prepared by the public administration.
"I also do not believe that if this were to happen, it would have an impact on the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals - one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years - has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, he said, would have meant postponing the benefits of the transformation into a digital form that included meeting public needs, which had not only a technical dimension, "because it covered economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system of State economic management, including a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the State executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of the Congress, ensures that laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly are enforced in the administrative sphere, he said.
In Michoacán, the possibility of counting "voice behind voice" is being analysed.
According to the data transferred to the PDP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total of 6,074 protocols.
The possibility of counting a voice-by-voice is real with regard to the election process this year in Michoacán, where, according to data from the Provisional Electoral Results Programme (PRI), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total of 6,074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacana Electoral Institute (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lyandral Saragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral corps had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with the federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, as the State Congress approved reforms shortly before their entry into force in this electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time-limits specified in the Act in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJ) decided on a constitutional claim made by the local legislature and declared "null and void and illegal" the voice of a State representative for constitutional reform, since he is not entitled to "permit or support them."
In an interview on the possibility of a "voice behind a voice," Maria de los Angeles Lianderal argued that, with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council, it would be possible to present a partial or full count of votes by a local electoral body.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more electoral boxes may be made on the condition that: the results of the protocols do not match; there is no voting record and the counting of documents in the urn or is not available to the President; or where there are obvious errors or corrections to the record.
In addition, there may be a general recalculation of votes in all election boxes when there is a sign that the difference between the proposed candidate for the election in question and those who obtained the second seat is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from a representative of the party and / or coalition that made the second of those candidates.
The total vote will also be recounted if, at the end of the normal counting, it is determined that the difference between the winner and the candidate who took second place is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate has taken second place, in the event that the ballot boxes that have been taken into account in the partial recalculation are excluded.
It is worth noting that in this situation there are elections in Morelia, where, according to the PRRA, the difference between the first and second places is only 0.16 per cent, even with 129 votes out of a total of 923.
