MSS declares the obesity gene search program.
Social protection leads a study on the search for the obesity gene of children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Protection (MSSI) announced that it was conducting a study to identify the obesity gene of children and young people, which had been called the protocol "Obesity genetics in childhood and adolescence," which would provide an estimate of the signs of overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, Head of the Medical Research Unit for Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietologists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Health Institute (NIPH) and the Centre for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invited the population (written or not) to participate in the MSSI sports centres participating in the study to the Mexico Valley, where children will be tested every Saturday, from 8 a.m. to 1 p.m..
He stressed that the protocol had begun to be maintained at the sports centre in Kuala Lumpur (western Mexico State) and that, since 8 October, activities had been held at the sports centre in Nesahualkoyotle (eastern Mexico State).
Once the goal of involving between 500 and 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Centre for Sport of Independence (South Mexico) and, finally, at the Morelos (North Mexico) Sports Centre.
He explained that the purpose of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify the risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day will be observed, with the main objective of bringing together 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14, with the permission of their parents and under their care, to fill out individual nutritional questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or renal deficiency.
He explained that, on Saturday, anthropometric measurements would be made of all participants (weight, growth and coverage of waist), measurement of blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes related to child obesity).
Cruz Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in child weight.
Medical studies carried out between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there has been an increase in only six years: 77 per cent of boys were obesity in the case of girls, 47 per cent; there was also a significant increase in weight, "said MSSI.
He said that the validity of the search for markers was based on the fact that the population of the country was different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, the Mexican was 65 per cent American, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and that the condition had an impact on the genes that were related to diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main consequence of obesity genetics was the inability of the body to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it was delayed as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark depots on the neck (acans) and forearm means that metabolism and even pre-diabetes are likely to break.
Information is provided with all confidentiality, and the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and changes in the way of life that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there were three main reasons for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sitting lifestyle, or a lack of daily physical activity, the holding of most of the day before the television, and the use of small-distance transport rather than walking.
It is also due to the high consumption of calories, that is, the increase in the use of sweet beverages and carbohydrates (Tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetic predisposition analysed in this programme.
The UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks.
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Department, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If attention were to be given to the signals sent by road cover, it would be necessary to repair some 200,000 miles per rainy season in the capital area of the Mexico Valley, as described by Rafael Herrera Naher, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Department, and add that if the construction and maintenance of the asphalt road surface were correct, the number could be reduced or reduced to zero at all.
In his lecture, the technological view of the International Year of Chemistry pits indicates that the laboratory for which it is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Errera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather was extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to prevent education.
He explained that the bitum, the largest part of the oil, was the sequence of the hydrocarbon molecules, some of the high molecular mass called asphalt, and others of the low molecular mass called Maltenes, which together gave the road cover its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The intuitive behaviour of the bitumen is that at a high heat rate of about 180 degrees, it acts as a liquid, at 120 of its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it remains almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, as stated by the chemical engineering expert.
A scientist from the chimfak observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered by flexible coatings, which were made up of six layers of material, of which the last three included bitumen.
Among the upper layers is a bitumen made of small stones, dropped into a bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this surface, he said, is submerged into a bitum.
When vehicles are moved and forces are applied, it helps the forces to be very well-distributed on the road.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt coated, he added, the last layer, which is called a layer of wear, which is made of a small stone, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with transport wheels, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these efforts, the wear layer also requires appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature changes, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it had a significant impact on the state of the asphalt.
When the earth is raw, the water penetrates the surface and it is difficult to get out of it, it causes all layers of the surface to be softened and thus education to be developed.
In education, he said, the first layer of wear was worn and only then it affected the bitumen, but the damage did not occur immediately, a process that should be addressed in the first signs of ongoing maintenance programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that the transport load was another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each surface should always be related to the transport load and that this requirement should be guaranteed in order to prevent frequent occurrence.
Rafael Herrera said that there was still a lot of work to be done on the bitumen, for example, on the bitumen emulsions that were already on the market in other countries and even helped to fix the holes with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
