North Flow, new gates for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North stream, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly to the Baltic Sea floor, has been launched.
It is designed to supply a gas equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas manufacturer, wanted to celebrate this event with the pompus.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the launch of the orchestra and the search for food, the opening of the North stream, a new gas pipeline that directly links Russia and Germany under the water.
The German Chancellor, Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fiyon and his Dutch colleague, Mart Rütte, together turned a symbolic valve to control the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline will provide 27.5 million additional cubic metres of gas each year to Western Europe through the first 1,224 km long pipeline linking the Leningrad region to the land of Meklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline should be ready at the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas equivalent to all French consumption.
The possibility of building a third pipeline on the same direction is already under discussion.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with a violent resistance from Poland and the Baltic States.
The Northern Flow will indeed allow the transport of gas directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose part of their power: they will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to deny access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Polt with the new "German-Soviet Pact," pointing to an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
It means that the question is politically sensitive.
In support of this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking more security of its supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has achieved its understanding of a direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are already at an end.
"This gas pipeline, part of cooperation with Russia, is a new artery that organically connects us," said François Fiyon, opening the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
This explains the wide smile on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Ljumin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical development.
The submarine is made of steel wrapped in concrete to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It's at the bottom of the sea, at a mean depth of 200 meters.
In order to build it, it was necessary to circumvent the minefields that had been left of the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, the press secretary of the North Potok company.
Many steps were also needed to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe is a long metal snake of a weight of 242 Eiffel towers, without rupture over its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but project managers abandoned it because Sweden was not happy that a Russian State company would be on its shores forever.
"In the event of an accident, we will close the gas flow in less than a minute," Jens Müller claims.
So, in the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But it seems unlikely to be a design that has designed stitches designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
The status of the gas pipeline will be monitored by a submarine robot that is pulling the ship for external observation, as well as by a transporter.
The cigar shall be injected into a 1-metre-diameter pipeline and pushed forward by a gas flow.
Upon arrival after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 metres per second, it shall provide accurate information on any metal deformation.
The gas pipeline was designed for 50 years without any need for repair.
The circulation of the gas is done only by its pressure.
It is 200 bar at the time of departure and 100 bar at the time of arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement the project.
The leader is Gazprom, who owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Netherlands Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture called the North Potok, which was charged with the construction and operation of a gas pipeline.
His headquarters is in Tsuga, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the company for 20 years, with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for the full volume, no matter how much gas is actually transported," Jens Müller states.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30 per cent of the shareholders and 70 per cent by bank loans.
The total cost of the work would be Euro7.4 million for two pipelines.
The GDF Suez investments will be about 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure they'll take their costs because Gazprom is taking all the risks.
The gas pipeline is coming out of the Baltic Sea in Ljumin on a sand bank planted by the softwood trees.
The valves are 4.5 metres high and form the gas output terminal.
The sensors shall measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it is pushed into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic metres of gas every hour.
It will be 3 million per hour at full capacity and 6 million in 2012.
